{{infobox Organization |name = International Business Education Alliance |image = IBEA_Official_Logo.png.gif |image_border = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = IBEA |motto = |formation = 2015 |extinction = |type = [[NGO]] |status = Active |purpose = |headquarters = [[Mannheim]], [[Baden-Württemberg]], Germany |location = |region_served = |membership = [[ESSEC]], [[University of Mannheim]], [[University of South Carolina]], [[Escola Brasileira de Administração Pública e de Empresas|Fundação Getúlio Vargas]] |language = |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{URL|http://www.ibea-bachelor.org/}} |remarks = }}
The '''International Business Education Alliance''' ('''IBEA''') is an exchange programme for undergraduate students in Business Administration. Besides studying at their home university, admitted undergraduate students participate in an extended bachelor's program that includes three exchange semesters at the participating institutions in the network. Participants are the [[University of Mannheim]] (Germany),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwl.uni-mannheim.de/en/home/|title=University of Mannheim Business School|publisher=uni-mannheim.de |accessdate=2015-12-03}}</ref> [[ESSEC|ESSEC Business School]] (France),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essec.edu|title=ESSEC Business School|publisher=essec.edu |accessdate=2015-12-03}}</ref> [[University of South Carolina|University of South Carolina, Darla Moore School of Business]] (United States),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moore.sc.edu/ |title=Darla Moore School of Business - University of South Carolina|publisher=moore.sc.edu |accessdate=2015-12-03}}</ref> and the [[Fundação Getúlio Vargas]] ([[Brazil]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.fgv.br/|title=FGV Business School|publisher=fgv.br |accessdate=2015-12-03}}</ref>
== History == IBEA was founded on August 1, 2015 when the deans of the respective business schools agreed to form the new partnership alliance IBEA. Its President is Jürgen M. Schneider, the dean of the University of Mannheim Business School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibea-bachelor.org/ |title=IBEA: The International Business Education Alliance |publisher=ibea-bachelor.org |date= |accessdate=2015-11-25}}</ref>
== Description == The IBEA program aims to provide undergraduate business students with a comprehensive view of the global environment of business. It consists of a four-year Bachelor program that draws on the academic expertise of each participating partner school. Selected students study part of the program as one cohort and stay one semester at each of the four participating institutions. Each school offers customized classes and cultural courses designed for IBEA students. Besides a local and regional exposure, students gain hands-on global management experience by working closely with one corporate partner from each school. The program started in fall 2015, with the first class of around 40 students expected to graduate in spring 2019. The first three semesters are completed at each student’s individual home institution. Beginning with the fourth semester, the IBEA students study for the subsequent four semesters, starting at the University of Mannheim, Business School, followed by the Darla Moore School of Business of the University of South Carolina and ESSEC’s newly inaugurated campus in [[Singapore]]. The last study abroad semester is spent at the Brazilian School of Public and Business Administration in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwl.uni-mannheim.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/press_releases/news/mit-dem-bachelor-um-die-welt-neue-auswahloption-im-mannheimer-bachelorprogramm-startet-ab-herbst-20/ |title=About: The International Business Education Alliance |publisher=University of Mannheim |accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://moore.sc.edu/academicprograms/undergraduate/majorsoffered/internationalbusiness/optionsoverviews/ibeamulticultural.aspx |title=About: The International Business Education Alliance |publisher=University of South Carolina |accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref>
